name: UNLV Tango Salsa Club
description:
UNLV Tango and Salsa club is dedicated to bringing the joy of social partner dancing to the UNLV community. 

We teach tango and salsa classes, organize social dance events and outings at UNLV, as well as at other Vegas venues, and promote social dancing through performances and outreach.

Everyone, from absolute beginners to experienced dancers is welcome to join the club.

Our emphasis is on sharing the dance experience in a safe, friendly, and encouraging environment.

name: Women's Lacrosse Practice
description:
Athletic? Love sports? Looking to join a club team? The UNLV Women’s Lacrosse team wants you! All interested players are welcome to come out – no previous experience is required.

If you are brand new to the sport, that is perfect! We love teaching the skills of the game and we have a lot of talented players and role models on the team that will help you pick up the game. Lacrosse is a spring sport but we play a less intense Fall season to prepare for the spring. What we have found helpful when we first started playing was googling or youtube-ing videos of women’s lacrosse games to see a little of how the game was played and then went onto www.uslacrosse.org to look at the rule book.

Please be on time and prepared with proper practice attire, water, stick, goggles, and mouth guard.

If you will not be able to make it or you will be late - you need to Coach Mitchell know as possible.

name: Thomas Society
description:
ach week this Fall will focus on a different topic representing the most frequently mentioned reasons people struggle with religion in general or Christianity in particular. This coming week (Sept. 19th) can be summed up in the question, "How could there be only one way to God?" 

Our weekly topic schedule will pretty closely match the chapters of the book "The Reason For God" by Timothy Keller. It was written by a pastor who spent years interviewing people about their greatest difficulies with Christianity and wanted to accurately summarize these concerns while offering an intelligent response. The first chapter deals with this week's question and is highly recommended for those participating as it summarizes the issues involved. You can find it here.http://www.amazon.com/The-Reason-God-Belief-Skepticism/dp/0525950494


For those who prefer to listen over reading, the author also gave a series of messages on the same topics here:
http://sermons.redeemer.com/store/index.cfm?fuseaction=category.display&category_id=29

If you want to know where I'm coming from, I've also spoken on most of these Fall's upcoming topics and posted them here:
http://www.cwrsouthvalley.com/series-

name: Human Trafficking: The Faces of Modern Day Slavery
description:
Want to learn more on how Human Trafficking is one of the most growing global epidemics?  Want to learn what YOU can do about it?

 Come join the UNLV Center for Social Justice (CSJ) in efforts to bring awareness to human trafficking.  The CSJ will be hosting “Human Trafficking: The Faces of Modern Day Slavery” on Tuesday, September 25that 6:00pm in the CSJ Library.  Guest Speakers Michael Lyle, from Not4Sale, and Jenny Heineman, from Sex Workers Outreach Program (SWOP), will be leading the discussion around human trafficking from a global, national, and local context.

If you have any additional questions regarding the event, please feel free to contact the UNLV Center for Social Justice at unlvcsj@unlv.edu or 702-895-4053.

Refreshments will be served.

This event is free and open to all students, faculty, and staff.

name: DASH: Delivering and Serving Hope
description: DASH seeks to address the problems of hunger and poverty by bridging the gap between UNLV students and the homeless population. By making, packing, and delivering peanut butter and jelly sandwich lunches, we hope to give students a glimpse of the plight of these disenfranchised populations and to give them a way to do something about it. After the program, we hope participants will take their involvement to the next level by seeking other ways to help the homeless community.

name: NBGSA Western Regional Conference
description:
The National Black Graduate Student Association (NBGSA) is pleased to announce Las Vegas, Nevada as the host site for its 2012 western regional conference. The NBGSA Western Regional Conference will be held October 12th-14th at the University of Nevada, Las Vegas. With the theme, "Scholars Achieving Graduate Excellence", NBGSA hopes to create a conference experience that assist scholars academically and personally, as well as give opportunities for students to network with professionals and fellow students.
 

Visit our Regional Conference website http://nbgsawest.webs.com/
